sudo dnf install -y \
  atk \
  at-spi2-atk \
  cups-libs \
  dbus-libs \
  libX11 \
  libXcomposite \
  libXdamage \
  libXrandr \
  libxcb \
  libxkbcommon \
  mesa-libgbm \
  alsa-lib \
  nss \
  pango \
  cairo \
  gtk3 \
  libdrm \
  libXcursor \
  libXinerama \
  libXScrnSaver \
  liberation-fonts \
  ca-certificates


Enable EPEL repository:Bash
sudo dnf install https://dl.fedoraproject.org/pub/epel/epel-release-latest-9.noarch.rpm   # For RHEL 9
# OR
sudo dnf install https://dl.fedoraproject.org/pub/epel/epel-release-latest-8.noarch.rpm   # For RHEL 8
(RHEL 8 only) 

Enable CodeReady Builder (required for some dependencies):Bashsudo subscription-manager repos --enable "codeready-builder-for-rhel-8-$(arch)-rpms"
Update the package list:Bashsudo dnf update
Install Chromium:Bashsudo dnf install chromium
Launch Chromium:
From the terminal: chromium or chromium-browser
Or find it in your applications menu.


Alternative: Using Snap (works on RHEL 7, 8, and 9)
If you prefer a self-contained version with automatic updates (and often the latest Chromium build):

Enable snapd:Bashsudo dnf install https://dl.fedoraproject.org/pub/epel/epel-release-latest-9.noarch.rpm   # For RHEL 9 (adjust for RHEL 8/7)
sudo dnf upgrade
sudo dnf install snapd
sudo ln -s /var/lib/snapd/snap /snap
sudo systemctl enable --now snapd.socket
Install Chromium via snap:Bashsudo snap install chromium
Launch it:Bashsnap run chromiumOr find it in the applications menu.

Note: Snap versions are usually newer and update automatically, but they are larger and sandboxed.

